  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀγαπᾷ γὰρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., he loveth our race; a philo-Jewish Pagan, whose affection for the people among whom he lived took the form of building a synagogue. Quite a credible fact, which could easily be ascertained. Herod built the temple. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Vide",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Lightfoot on this.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he loveth our nation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This shews that the centurion was a Gentile,—probably a proselyte of the gate (though the term was invented later), i.e. one of those who embraced Judaism on the whole, but without becoming a ‘proselyte of righteousness’ by accepting circumcision. It is not impossible that he may have been a Roman, though there is no ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "direct",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " proof that Romans ever held such offices under Herod Antipas. More probably he was some Greek or Syrian, holding a commission under the tetrarch.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he hath built us a synagogue",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "our Synagogue he himself built for us. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The expression, “the synagogue,” does not necessarily imply that there was only one synagogue in Capernaum, but only that he had built the one from which this deputation came, which was probably the chief synagogue of Capernaum. If Capernaum be Tel Hum (as I became convinced on the spot itself), then the ruins of it shew that it probably possessed two synagogues; and this we should have conjectured beforehand, seeing that Jerusalem is said to have had 400. The walls of one of these, built of white marble, are of the age of the Herods, and stand just above the lake. It may be the very building here referred to. This liberality on the part of the Gentiles was by no means unfrequent. Wealthy Gentile proselytes not seldom sent splendid gifts to the Temple itself. The Ptolemies, Jos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Antt.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " xii. 2, § 5; Sosius, id. xiv. 16, § 4; Fulvia, id. xviii. 3, § 5, &c. See on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 21:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἀγαπᾷ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he loveth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") A feeling which is rare in a Roman soldier.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γὰρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") It was in a different thing that his chief ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "worthiness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " lay, namely, in his ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "faith",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "αὐτὸς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "himself",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of himself, of his own accord. This act, viz. his building a synagogue, was something greater and more rare than his loving their nation.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ᾠκοδόμησεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he has built",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") at his own expense, or by his command: not merely did he not (as others) profane and violate a synagogue.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Luke 7:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He hath built (αὐτὸς ᾠκοδόμησεν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He is emphatic; himself, at his own expense.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A synagogue (τὴν συναγωγὴν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The article, \"the synagogue,\" marks the particular synagogue which these elders represented. Hence Rev., rightly, \"our synagogue.\" \"He did not merely avoid profaning the synagogue\" (Bengel). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]